---
import Article from '../layouts/Article.astro';

const title = 'Funscripts from your Stash & XBVR library - browse, stream, generate';
const description =
  'FunGen connects to your Stash and XBVR media servers, browses their scene library inside the app, streams a scene directly, and generates an AI funscript from it - no downloading, no copying files.';
const canonicalPath = '/stash-xbvr-funscripts';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const articleLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Generate funscripts from Stash and XBVR',
  description,
  inLanguage: 'en',
  dateModified: '2026-07-17',
  mainEntityOfPage: 'https://fungen.app/stash-xbvr-funscripts',
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'FunGen' },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'FunGen',
    logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://fungen.app/icon-512.png' },
  },
};
const breadcrumbs = [{ name: 'Stash & XBVR', path: '/stash-xbvr-funscripts' }];
---

<Article
  {title}
  {description}
  heading="Funscripts from your Stash & XBVR library"
  {canonicalPath}
  {articleLd}
  {breadcrumbs}
>
  <p class="lead">
    Already organise your collection in <strong>Stash</strong> or <strong>XBVR</strong>? FunGen reads
    from them directly. It finds your servers on the network, browses their scene library inside the
    app, streams a scene without downloading it, and generates an
    <a href={`${base}/generate-funscripts-from-video/`}>AI funscript</a> from it - one workflow, no
    copying files around.
  </p>

  <h2>It finds your servers automatically</h2>
  <p>
    Open FunGen and it sweeps your local network for <strong>Stash</strong> and <strong>XBVR</strong>
    instances, offering each one as a one-click connect on the Welcome page. A password-protected
    Stash prompts for its API key inline; servers on another subnet or a VPN / Tailscale address can
    be added by hand in Preferences. XBVR needs nothing but the connection.
  </p>

  <h2>Browse the whole library, in the app</h2>
  <p>
    Connected scenes show up as their own browse sections - <strong>XBVR scenes</strong> and
    <strong>Stash scenes</strong> each get a collapsible, searchable grid with the server's own cover
    art. Scroll a library of thousands; search narrows it instantly. FunGen respects what each server
    already knows: scenes flagged interactive, existing funscripts, VR versus 2D.
  </p>

  <h2>Stream a scene and script it</h2>
  <p>
    Click a scene and FunGen <strong>streams it straight from the server</strong> - Stash's stream
    endpoint or XBVR's DMS URL - so nothing is copied to your disk. From there it's the normal FunGen
    flow: generate a stroke script with AI, or full <a href={`${base}/funscripts-for-osr2-sr6/`}
      >multi-axis</a
    > motion for <a href={`${base}/vr-funscripts/`}>VR</a>, then refine it on the
    <a href={`${base}/funscript-editor/`}>timeline</a>. If the server already has a funscript for the
    scene, FunGen loads it alongside the video so you can play or edit it right away.
  </p>

  <h2>Play it to your device</h2>
  <p>
    The script drives whatever hardware you own - <a href={`${base}/funscripts-for-the-handy/`}
      >The Handy</a
    >, OSR2 / SR6, or anything on <a href={`${base}/supported-devices/`}>Buttplug.io / Intiface</a> -
    with per-device interpolation and latency compensation. FunGen can even serve the session to a
    phone or VR headset while the device follows.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it's set up this way</h2>
  <p>
    Your library lives where you already keep it. FunGen doesn't ask you to re-import, duplicate, or
    move anything - it connects, reads, streams, and generates. Stash and XBVR stay the source of
    truth for your collection; FunGen is the piece that turns any scene in it into motion.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a href={`${base}/`}>Download FunGen</a> and point it at your Stash or XBVR server - free to try.
  </p>
</Article>
